MATLAB Implementation
Model Parameters
k = 800;      % Spring stiffness [N/m]
c = 2;        % Damping coefficient [Ns/m]
delta = 0.5;  % Spring free length [m]
m = 30;       % Vehicle mass [kg]
g = 9.81;     % Gravitational acceleration [m/s^2]
Road Excitation
A = 0.05;      % Road profile amplitude [m]
omega = 1;     % Excitation angular frequency [rad/s]
Simulation Parameters
t_final = 60;     % Simulation time [s]
n = 1000;         % Number of samples
delta_t = t_final / n;

Initial conditions:

t = 0;
x_i = 0;
vel_x_i = 0;
Numerical Integration

At each time step the algorithm:

Computes the external excitation.
Evaluates the vehicle acceleration.
Updates velocity using Euler integration.
Updates displacement.
Stores the simulation results.

The integration loop is implemented as

for cont = 1:n

    % External excitation

    Fest = k*delta - m*g + ...
           k*A*sin(omega*t) + ...
           c*A*omega*cos(omega*t);

    % Euler integration

    acc_ii = (-c*vel_x_i - k*x_i + Fest)/m;

    vel_x_ii = vel_x_i + acc_ii*delta_t;

    x_ii = x_i + vel_x_ii*delta_t;

    % Save current values

    vet_x(cont) = x_i;
    vet_t(cont) = t;

    % Update time

    t = t + delta_t;

    % Update state variables

    vel_x_i = vel_x_ii;
    x_i = x_ii;

end
Results

The simulation produces the vertical displacement of the vehicle body as a function of time.

The resulting graph exhibits a sinusoidal response due to the harmonic road excitation acting on the suspension system.

This exercise demonstrates the numerical solution of the equation of motion of a quarter-car suspension model using the Explicit Euler method.
